Experiment 10: Shell Script for If-Else Statements
The Script (conditional.sh)
This script demonstrates how to handle numerical comparisons (even/odd) and check file properties.

Bash
#!/bin/bash
echo "--- If-Else Conditional Demonstration ---"

# Example 1: Check if a number is Even or Odd
echo -n "Enter a number: "
read num
if [ $((num % 2)) -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "Result: $num is an Even number."
else
    echo "Result: $num is an Odd number."
fi
echo "---------------------------------------"

# Example 2: Check if a user is eligible to vote
echo -n "Enter your age: "
read age
if [ $age -ge 18 ]; then
    echo "Status: You are eligible to vote."
else
    stop_age=$((18 - age))
    echo "Status: You are not eligible. Wait $stop_age more year(s)."
fi
echo "---------------------------------------"

# Example 3: Check if a file exists (Useful for OS tasks)
echo -n "Enter a filename to check: "
read filename
if [ -f "$filename" ]; then
    echo "File '$filename' exists in this directory."
else
    echo "File '$filename' does not exist."
fi
Short Description for GitHub
Title: Implementation of Decision Making in Shell Scripting.

This experiment demonstrates the use of if-else blocks to control the execution flow of a script based on specific conditions.
Key Syntax used:
if [ condition ]; then ... else ... fi
Comparison Operators: >    * -eq (Equal to)
-ne (Not equal to)
-gt (Greater than)
-ge (Greater than or equal to)
-lt (Less than)
File Test: -f checks if a regular file exists.

How to Run:
Save the code as exp10.sh.
Open the terminal and run: chmod +x exp10.sh
Execute it using: ./exp10.sh
